1. e4 {Notes by C. von Bardeleben} e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6
4. Bb5 a6 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 7. Nxe4 Qd4 8. O-O Qxe5
9. Re1 Be6 10. d4 Qf5 {This move is better than Qd5, for the
latter move would be followed by 11 Bg5 (!) and if f6 (?) 12
Bxf6.}11. Bg5 h6 12. Qd3 {!} Kd7 {This is somewhat
dangerous. Black ought to have played Qa5 13 Ba4 Qh5; of
course he cannot play 12...hxg5 because of 13 Nd6+, winning
the Queen.} 13. Bh4 Re8 14. Re3 Bd6 15. Rae1 Qb5 16. Nxd6 cxd6
17. Qa3 a5 18. c3 Qb6 19. Bg3 Qc7 20. c4 {This sacrifice leads
to a clear draw. If White prepared the advance of the Queen’s
Bishop’s Pawn by 20 b3, he would have a good attack; the
continuation might be then b5 21 Rc1 Rd8 22 c4 bxc4 23 bxc4 c5
24 d5 Bf5 25 Rce1(!), with an excellent game.} Bxc4 21. Rxe8
Rxe8 22. Rxe8 Kxe8 23. Bxd6 Qd7 24. Qe3+ Be6 25. Bc5 f6 26. a3
Kf7 27. Qg3 Bd5 28. h3 Qe6 29. f3 Qe3+ 30. Qf2 Qb3 31. Kh2 b6
32. Bd6 Be6 33. Qd2 h5 34. Bc7 a4 35. Bg3 b5 36. Be1 Bf5
37. Qf2 Qc2 38. Qxc2 Bxc2 {After the exchange of the Queens
there is not the slightest doubt that the result of the
struggle will be a draw.} 39. Kg1 Ke6 40. Kf2 Kd5 41. Ke3 Kc4
42. g3 Bd3 43. Bc3 Bf1 44. h4 Bh3 1/2-1/2